column50: Kai's lesson was well developed and delivered.  Kai had good knowledge of what he was teaching and what he was expecting from his students.
column54: There is an excellent environment for learning established.  There is a great deal of respect for student to student and teacher to student and vice-versa.  There is a cohesion of expectations from all adults in the classroom.  Students were well engaged, accommodations and modifications were made as necessary.  There is a warmth one feels when they walk into the classroom.  During this lesson, there were no behavior outsbursts.  Students definitely are aware of procedures and what is expected of them.
column58: Kai causes his students to think critically.  Even students that had the same answer, he asked them to find another term to use.  This lesson was highly engaging and allowed students to work together, as well as individually.  Students also were capable of using their Airbooks as a tool.  Kai was constantly assessing his students by circulating amongst them and asking them questions to be sure they had mastery.  His questions caused student to think critically and were used as part of his assessment of their understanding of the lesson.
column60: Kai is always reflecting on his teaching and being aware of the mastery of the information taught.  He then using this information for his next steps.

column50: Gabrielle has established a safe, caring environment.  Her lesson was well developed and delivered.  She was well prepared with all materials needed.  She also made this lesson relevant to her students using materials they were all familiar with.  She knew exactly where this lesson was heading and what the expected outcomes were.
column54: Gabrielle's classroom is print rich, very colorful and student centered.  She has a behavior management system in place, that the students are all aware of and buy into.  The students were so engaged that their were no behavior management problems during this lesson.  Students followed routines and Gabrielle used transition time wisely.  The rules are posted and students are expected to follow them.  The flow of the day also helps create a culture of learning.  Gabrielle has an excellent rapport with her students.
column58: Gabrielle encouraged students to work with partners to help accomplish the task.  Students were highly engaged in this activity and were involved from the beginning of the lesson until the end.  Gabrielle worked with each table to be sure the students were achieving mastery, thus assessing what her next steps need to be.
column60: Gabrielle always reflects well on her lessons and takes the information learned to develop her next lessons.

column50: Nicole knows her content area and developed a good lesson with an expected outcome.  Nicole tends to 'stick to the script' and misses out on teachable moments.
column54: Nicole had no difficulties with managing student behavior as this lesson was highly engaging.  She has developed better classroom management skills, but has room for improvement.  Her classroom layout has changed for the better, giving her more space and allowing for more computers.  There are reference tables and student work displayed.  She has established a very visual word wall.  She has a good rapport with her students.
column58: Nicole needs to work on her discussion techniques.  She doesn't ask students to think further upon the questions asked.  She likes to follow her script, even though students asked very good questions, but did not got responses. This particular lesson was very engaging and interactive.  There was group work,individual work and whole class activities.  The assignment was very relevant to the students.  She was using this lesson as an assessment of what students learned about measurement and how well they could properly use a ruler.  She stated that she would use this information in creating future lessons.
column60: Nicole does reflect on her teaching, even though she has a hard time accepting constructive criticism.  She does listen to it and follow through on it, but has difficulty accepting it at first.

column50: Fizza's science mini-lesson on static electricity was carefully constructed and implemented to include multi-sensory, visual, auditory, kinesthetic, and differentiated learning activities, including four versions of the student activity worksheets to align with each student's linguistic skills (more challenging worksheets with questions and multiple choice responses for the student who can read, fill-in the-blank with words for the student who can read and write with help, and two versions using PECS symbols to help students identify the steps in the electricity experiment for pre-verbal students who are not readers.
column54: Student behavior has generally been appropriate.  Using a combination of consistent positive reinforcement with firm, but respectful and consistent communication of established standards of behavior has made a big difference in modifying the most inappropriate misbehavior.
column58: Ms. Siddiqui regularly uses ongoing daily assessments for small group and individual instruction, resulting in accurate feedback that advances individual student learning and helps to guide lesson design and planning.
column60: Ms. Siddiqui makes an accurate and thoughtful assessment of her lesson's effectiveness.  She continues to work on enhancing lesson design through fine-tuning of questioning techniques, individual student assessments to drive differentiated instruction, and accessing age-appropriate resources for work station task kits to support student learning styles and enhance greater independence.

column50: Kamara's lesson was well developed and delivered.  Kamara had good knowledge of what she was teaching and what she was expecting from her students.  She needed to be able to incorporate some of the students'questions into the class discussion.  She missed a few opportunities for 'teachable moments'.
column54: It is apparent that Kamara has established routines in the classroom, as students knew what to do when entering her room.  She has established a very warm learning environment that is safe and caring.  Her lesson was engaging and thus there were no behavior problems.
column58: Kamara involved her students in the lesson, by asking them to read to each other aloud and by offering questions for discussion.  Students were engaged throughout the lesson.  She needs to look for and use 'teachable moments' and not solely follow a script. Kamara did questioning students throughout the lesson, checking for understanding.  Students were also given exit tickets to be sure they understood what was taught and were given appropriate homework.
column60: Kamara reflected on the lesson and felt it went well.  She also discussed with me that the atmosphere took time to create.  I acknowledged the fact that a good learning environment had been created.

column50: Alexa's science/literacy lesson on formulating the hypothesis for their science project was well designed.  The lesson on human body systems was differentiated and aligned to the ability levels of each homogeneous group of students.  The lessons were developed with reading passages that involved simpler body systems for students with lower literacy levels and more complex systems for the higher-level groups for her English language learners.  Alexa worked hard to scaffold the learning activities for her students who have had limited school experience in their native language and little schooling in their native country, so worksheets and graphic organizers were differentiated in both English and English and Spanish, depending on their English proficiency and literacy levels.
column54: Student behavior has generally been appropriate.  Alexa responds with preventive actions when a student appears to interrupt student learning, and is sensitive and respectful to individual student needs.  By keeping students actively engaged and attentive throughout the lesson, Alexa is able to maintain established standards of conduct.
column58: Alexa uses multiple strategies to assess student learning throughout the science lesson. Alexa used the share that followed the students' work on the "Do Now" as an assessment or a gauge of their understanding of what a claim needs to include.  She asked the students to reflect on their work on the prior lesson to help them decide which of the three claims is the best one, and explain why (higher order thinking).  Additionally, Alexa used a variety of questioning strategies, including skill-based, as well as higher order questions. Alexa circulated to each group and approved the testable claim that they wrote, and also assessed their understanding of the remaining steps on the graphic organizer as they worked independently or with their group members.
column60: Alexa has made a thoughtful assessment of the lesson's effectiveness and made suggestions of what could be tried to improve the lesson.  Alexa would like to improve on scaffolding the learning activities for students who have had limited school experience in their native language and also differentiate the steps in the lesson to accommodate their needs.  Alexa is working on finding more effective higher order questions for advanced students, and will work on developing student critical thinking skills for higher level kids.

column50: John sets up a safe, caring environment for his students.  He is soft spoken and gives verbal praise as it is due.  He knows his content well, is well prepared and delivers his lesson well.  He uses all types of instructional materials to keep his students motivated and engaged.
column54: John has definitely set up a climate for learning.  Students know their routines and follow through on what is asked of them.  The assignments are well prepared so that procedures can be easily followed and students are engaged.  Therefore, there are no behaviors to deal with.  John is encouraging and casues students to think critically and stay focus to achieve mastery.
column58: John does all of these things well.  He asks questions that are relevant and require critical thinking. When necessary he rephrases them or gives examples of what he is looking for. He has a good rapport with his students that encourages students to participate.  The students he was working with needed to be guided to a discussion and John did this well.  He had the students speaking to each other, even though both are rather shy.  John was very good in explaining the topic and showing a video that expressed irony.  He let the students explain where the irony was and why.  He also asked students to explain situations they were in that showed irony.
column60: John reflects easily on his teaching. He realized he was not using wait time effectively when we debriefed.He constantly looks at how students respond and changes his teaching so that all students can succeed and achieve mastery.

column50: Marcella did a great job of showing the knowledge she had of the topic.  She was teaching students how to read a political cartoon.She was using it as a segue to her full lesson.  In addition to the cartoon she used a video that she played, stopped and discussed checking for understanding. She has an excellent rapport with her students and her classroom is print rich.  She has a word wall and reference material all over the room, as well as student work displayed.
column54: Marcella does this all well.  Procedures are followed, students are engaged and there are no behavior problems. All of her materials were ready for her students.  She started class on time, and as students came in they took their seats and began their work.
column58: Marcella asked all the right critcial thinking questions to obtain the answers from her students.  As difficult as it was to decipher the cartoon, her questions elicited the correct responses.  The cartoon was relevant to both today's society as well as connected to the lesson she was going to teach.  The students had a sheet to follow during the video.  Marcella stopped the video each time making sure students were following the content and doing the work. She uses an exit ticket to further assess where her students are at.
column60: Marcella has no problem reflecting on her teaching.  She felt this lesson went well and teaches which ever students are in her classroom.

column50: Shatiqua knows her content and is confident in the way she teaches it.She definitely had outcomes in her lesson and worked towards them as she taught.  The lesson went smoothly as far as how it was organized and presented.
column54: Shatiqua tried very hard to set up a safe, caring environment which she did for the most part.  When students were not engaged, she tended to yell at the class.  She did have difficulty with one particular student, and the school is working on his behavior.
column58: Shatiqua asked very good critical thinking questions and her assignments were too. However, because of the behaviors being exhibited, it was difficult to totally engage students.  However, when students were assigned to groups, 4 of them worked well and the noise level decreased.  Shatiqua still needed to work on controlling the behavior of the young man in her room.  Most of Shatiqua's assessment was from her questions and from checking in with students in their groups.
column60: Shatiqua felt this lesson went better than some of her others.  She agreed that she needed to work on her own frustrations with the behaviors exhibited by some, in particular the young man.

column54: The teacher manages classroom procedures well with little loss of instructional time. Students follow established routines. The teacher monitors student behavior closely. Response to student misbehavior is consistent.
column58: The teacher engages all students in the learning process. Learning tasks are aligned with instructional outcomes.  The teacher needs to engage the students in more discussion and encourage them to respond to one another.

column50: Ted is well versed in the content knowledge.  He planned and executed his lesson well.  He differentiated assignments for his students and used accommodations and modifications as necessary.  The material presented was age appropriate and relevant.
column54: Ted has established a very safe, caring learning environment.  The room is print rich.  All of his paraprofessionals work with him to help students meet mastery levels. The students are aware of routines and follow them easily.  His lesson was motivating and engaging and there were no behavior issues.
column58: Ted's lesson was very engaging.  The morning news was differentiated so that the material for each student was appropriate for that student.  While showing the CNN News, he stopped and checked for understanding, which he used to assess where his students were at. Ted is using more questions and his questions are becoming those that require more critical thinking.
column60: Ted is always looking at how his lesson is going.  He is always open to constructive criticism and uses it to improve his teaching technique.

column50: Alana planned her lesson well and taught it, but with little student engagement.  She had outcomes set, and her lesson did have a beginning, middle and end, but needed a stronger delivery.
column54: Alana was just assigned this room and is in the process of setting it up, including technology.  She has a good relationship with her students, but needs to develop it further. column50: This was a very creative lesson that focused on the differences between physical and chemical changes.  The traditional mini-lesson was followed with a number of guided practice activities under teacher supervision and concluded with students creating their own T-charts showing examples of differences between the two states.  Students posted their work for display around the room and table groups then circulated among the postings to record their comments.
column54: The teacher's expectations for high levels of learning were clearly displayed.  Classroom time was maximized due to excellent routines and procedures that have been clearly established.
column58: A hallmark of this lesson was the high degree of student participation.  In addition to some Talk and Turn opportunities, students were broken into table-groups to create T-charts identifying real life reactions (i.e., frying an egg, food beginning to mold, etc.) as either physical or chemical changes.  When these T-charts were posted around the room, table-groups were then challenged to circulate among them to record their comments with magic markers.  All 30 students present were thoroughly engaged and stimulated.
column60: Ms. Gentile is thoughtful and reflective about her practice.  She is currently working on expanding her differentiation skills for her ELL students.

Students used molecular model kits to illustrate how many electrons each atom will share when forming a compound.  This was a fine example of rigorous, important learning in the discipline.
column54: This was a well behaved, orderly class of 28 students primarily due to the routines and procedures that the teacher has established.  As a consequence, very little instructional time, if any at all, was lost due to unnecessary activity.
column58: Mr. Wong circulated among the eight lab tables, prompting greater understanding by posing questions and guiding procedures.  He also used the opportunity to assess and monitor student progress.
column60: To improve lesson effectiveness, we agreed that Mr. Wong would focus greater attention on using the Aim both as a hook to establish the purpose of the lesson and as a tool to develop a summary of knowledge learned. column50: This was a well-structured lesson moving through all the appropriate parts of a sound pedagogical design.  However, the goal (examining the effect of exercise on one's heart rate) lacked rigor in that students already knew the answer from general knowledge/experience even before they walked into the room.  Furthermore, the lab activity (walking in place, jogging and resting) only confirmed what they already knew.  To strengthen this lesson, we discussed how rigor could have been added by investigating the effects of exercise on breathing rates, sweat output, etc. in addition to heart rate.
column54: Mr. Burns employed a number of excellent techniques to inhibit misbehavior and off task activity.  He has established effective routines and procedures and displayed a great deal of confidence and maturity.
column58: The lab was creative in that it had students read their own pulse rates when at rest, and then after moderate exercise, and then again after rigorous exercise.  Although students recorded their data, the teacher never paused to have them share out their findings.  It was a missed opportunity to "play" with the material to get the youngsters intellectually energized as they were physically energized.
column60: Mr. Burns was quick to confirm that youngsters weren't as stimulated or engaged as he had hoped for.  We agreed that he will focus his attention on increasing the rigor of his goals, questions and expectations.
